      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <p>Common questions about emergency electrical repair in Utah.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>What should I do if I lose power in part of my house?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>First, check your electrical panel for tripped breakers and try resetting them once. If the breaker trips again immediately, do not keep resetting it -- this indicates a fault that needs professional diagnosis. Check whether neighbors have power to rule out a utility outage. If the problem is isolated to your home, call <a href="tel:801-885-4521">801-885-4521</a> for diagnosis and repair.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>Do you offer emergency electrical service?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>Yes. Osborne Electric provides emergency electrical repair services for situations that pose safety hazards, such as exposed wiring, burning smells, sparking outlets, and complete power loss. Call <a href="tel:801-885-4521">801-885-4521</a> and we will prioritize your call to get your home safe as quickly as possible.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>How much does emergency electrical repair cost?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>Emergency electrical repair costs vary depending on the nature of the problem. Simple breaker replacements or loose connections may cost $150 to $300. More complex issues like storm damage or failed panels may cost more. Osborne Electric provides a clear diagnosis and upfront pricing before beginning any repair work.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>What causes a circuit breaker to keep tripping?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>Repeated breaker trips are typically caused by an overloaded circuit, a short circuit in the wiring, a ground fault, or a failing breaker. Overloads happen when too many devices draw power from one circuit. Short circuits and ground faults indicate wiring problems that need professional repair. A licensed electrician can diagnose the exact cause and fix it safely.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>Can storm damage affect my home's electrical system?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>Yes. Lightning strikes, power surges, fallen trees, and wind damage can all affect your home's electrical system. Storm damage may cause panel failures, damaged wiring, blown circuits, or damaged meter bases. After a severe storm, have a licensed electrician inspect your system if you experience any electrical irregularities.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

